 |filename = If You Had My Love (Edit).ogg
 |title = "If You Had My Love" (Radio Edit)
 |description = A twenty second sample of the radio edit of "If You Had My Love", one of 1999's most "infectious singles".<ref>http://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=348&dat=20010130&id=0cYvAAAAIBAJ&sjid=PzUDAAAAIBAJ&pg=1737,9846654</ref>
}}

Lopez's debut single, "[[If You Had My Love]]", was released in May 1999.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/news/jennifer-lopez-readies-first-album-946511.story |title=Jennifer Lopez Readies First Album |publisher=Billboard.com |date=April 15, 1999 |accessdate=2012-07-01}}</ref> The song was a commercial success worldwide, peaking atop of the charts in Australia, Canada, Finland, the Netherlands, New Zealand and the United States, and within the top ten in ten other countries. "[[No Me Ames]]", a duet with American recording artist [[Marc Anthony]] was released as a [[B-side]] to "If You Had My Love" and as the album's second single.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.amazon.com/If-You-Had-Love-Ames/dp/B00000IYVB/ref=sr_1_2?ie=UTF8&qid=1336244077&sr=8-2 |title=If You Had My Love / No Me Ames: Jennifer Lopez, Marc Anthony: Music |publisher=Amazon.com |date= |accessdate=2012-05-05}}</ref> The song was promoted by [[Sony Music Latin|Sony Discos]], who released a salsa and a ballad version of the song on their respective radio formats.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://books.google.com/?id=kw0EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA107&dq=intitle:billboard+%22no+me+ames%22#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Latin Acts Get Retail, Radio Boosts Via Dual Singles|last=Lannert|first=John|volume=112|issue=2|page=107|date= January 8, 2000|accessdate=2012-05-05|work=Billboard|unused_data=Prometheus Global Media}}</ref> The surprising success of ''On the 6'' made the "popular actor even more popular". Both the music industry and the public became intrigued by "this woman who seemed to have so many different talents".<ref name="Latin Sensations">{{cite book|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=q1BW88v0_zMC&pg=PA47&dq=jennifer+lopez+latin+soul&hl=en&sa=X&ei=ob_yT42sAcqjrQGGgs2JCQ&ved=0CDEQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=jennifer%20lopez%20latin%20soul&f=false |title=Latin Sensations – Herón Márquez – Google Books |publisher=Books.google.com |date= |accessdate=2012-07-03}}</ref> "[[Waiting for Tonight]]" was the third single, which met a peak of eight on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100.<ref>{{cite web|title=Waiting For Tonight – Richie Jones|url=http://www.billboard.com/#/song/jennifer-lopez/waiting-for-tonight/1832665|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] (billboard.com)|accessdate=2012-01-29|author=Billboard.com}}</ref> The album produced two other singles—"[[Feelin' So Good]]" and "[[Let's Get Loud (Jennifer Lopez song)|Let's Get Loud]]"—which each attained moderate success.<ref name="Feelin' So Good">{{Cite album-notes |title=Jennifer Lopez: Feelin' So Good |artist=Jennifer Lopez |year=2000 |format=Booklet |publisher=[[SMV Enterprises]], a division of [[Sony Music Entertainment|SME]] |location=[[New York City]], [[New York|NY]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1431392/jennifer-lopez-offers-new-album-update.jhtml |title=News – Articles – 1431392 |publisher=Mtv.com |date=August 8, 2000 |accessdate=2012-03-10}}</ref> "Waiting for Tonight" (2000) and "Let's Get Loud" (2001) each received [[Grammy Award]] nominations in the [[Best Dance Recording]] category.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rockonthenet.com/archive/2001/grammys.htm |title=43rd Grammy Awards – 2001 |publisher=Rockonthenet.com |date=February 21, 2001 |accessdate=2011-08-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rockonthenet.com/archive/2000/grammys.htm |title=42nd Grammy Awards – 2000 |publisher=Rockonthenet.com |date=February 23, 2000 |accessdate=2011-08-06}}</ref> Additionally, "No Me Ames" received two nominations at the 2000 [[Latin Grammy Awards]]. By the end of 1999, Lopez had successfully converted herself from a [[film star]] to a [[pop star]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Puff Daddy out on bail|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/579912.stm|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=2012-01-29|date=Tuesday, December 28, 1999}}</ref>

[[File:Jennifer-lopez-green-versace-dress.jpg|thumb|190px|left|Lopez at the [[42nd Grammy Awards]] in 2000]]

On December 27, 1999, Lopez and [[Sean Combs]] were at Club New York, a midtown Manhattan nightclub, when gunfire erupted between Combs' entourage and another group. Lopez and Combs were being driven away from the scene when they were chased and stopped by the police. A gun was found in the front seat of their vehicle. Combs was charged with felony gun possession. Stress over Combs' trial and pursuit by the press multiplied their problems and Lopez terminated her involvement with Combs a year later.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F40A12F6395E0C778DDDA80894D8404482 |title=Puffy Combs Is Indicted In Club Case |author=[[David S. Rohde]] |accessdate=2007-01-13 |work=The New York Times |date=January 14, 2000}}</ref> Lopez controversially arrived at the [[42nd Grammy Awards]] on February 22, 2000 wearing a plunging exotic green [[Versace]] silk chiffon dress, which became known as the [[Green Versace dress of Jennifer Lopez|Green Versace Jungle Dress]]. The dress, known for its low cut neck that extended before her navel and its open back, generated much controversy and media attention. Images of Lopez in the green dress were downloaded from the Grammy website 642,917 times in just 24 hours after the event.<ref name="Lee2003">{{cite book|last=Lee|first=Michelle|title=Fashion victim: our love-hate relationship with dressing, shopping, and the cost of style|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=E3eBAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=2011-05-16|date=February 11, 2003|publisher=Broadway Books|isbn=978-0-7679-1048-4|page=122}}</ref> Lopez was surprised by the enormous media coverage, declaring that "It was a nice dress. I had no idea it was going to become such a big deal".<ref name="OTD">{{cite web|url=http://onthisdayinfashion.com/?p=11475|title=J.Lo Helps Put Donatella—and Herself—on the Fashion Map in That Green Dress|publisher=On This Day in Fashion|date=February 23, 2001|last=Chambers|first=Rachel|accessdate=2011-05-16}}</ref> Returning to film, Lopez starred opposite [[Vincent D'Onofrio]], in the [[psychological thriller]] film ''[[The Cell]]'', released on August 18, 2000.<ref>{{cite web|last=Travers|first=Peter|title=The Cell Movie Review|url=http://www.rollingstone.com/movies/reviews/the-cell-20000818|work=Rolling Stone|publisher=(rollingstone.com)|accessdate=2012-01-30|date=August 18, 2000}}</ref> She portrayed Catherine Deane, a child psychologist who uses [[virtual reality]] to enter into the minds of her patients to coax them out of their comas. ''The Cell'' achieved Box Office success.<ref name="MSNbio"/><ref>{{cite news|last=Pearlman|first=Cindy|title=Living la vida Lopez isn't easy |accessdate=2012-01-30|newspaper=The Record|date=August 17, 2000}}</ref>

Knowing how important it was to stay fresh and innovate the music industry, Lopez decided to change her image to keep her fans guessing. She dyed her hair and renamed herself J.Lo, a nickname which her fans began to call her on the streets after she began her recording career in 1999.<ref name="BookJLo">{{cite book|title=Divas of the new Millennium|year=2005|page=108|url=http://books.google.com/?id=1ZGMcUEvkyEC&pg=PA104&dq=Jennifer+Lopez+if+you+had+my+love#v=onepage&q&f=false|coauthors=Stacy Deanne, Kelly Kenyatta, Natasha Lowery, Kwynn Sanders|isbn=9780974977966|author1=Deanne|first1=Stacy|last2=Kenyatta|last3=Lowery|last4=Sanders}}</ref> Her second studio album, entitled ''[[J.Lo (album)|J.Lo]]'', was released on January 22, 2001. It sold 272,000 copies in its opening week and debuted atop the ''Billboard'' 200—the same week her [[romantic comedy]] film ''[[The Wedding Planner]]'' led box office receipts—making Lopez the first female to have a film and album number one at the same time.<ref name="movie and album">{{cite web|title=Jennifer Lopez Tops With Moviegoers, Music Buyers|url=http://www.vh1.com/news/articles/1438902/20010131/index.jhtml|publisher=VH1 (vh1.com)|accessdate=2012-01-29|date=January 2001}}</ref><ref name=dethroned>{{cite web|title=Lopez Bows At No. 1; O-Town, Dream Debut High5|url=http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/news/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=474548&zxtmsessid=4459230781#/bbcom/news/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=474548&zxtmsessid=4459230781|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] (billboard.com)|author=Billboard}}</ref><ref name="timeTyrangiel"/><ref name="timeTyrangiel">{{cite news |url=http://www.time.com/time/nation/article/0,8599,1093638,00.html |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20090301064251/http://www.time.com/time/nation/article/0,8599,1093638,00.html |archivedate=2009-03-01 |title=Jennifer Lopez |author=[[Josh Tyrangiel]] |accessdate=2007-01-13 |work=Time |date=August 13, 2005}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/news/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=474548&zxtmsessid=4459230781|title=Lopez Bows At No. 1; O-Town, Dream Debut High5|last=Cohen|first=Jonathan|date=January 31, 2001|work=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc|accessdate=2009-06-22}}</ref> "[[Love Don't Cost a Thing (song)|Love Don't Cost a Thing]]" was released as the first single from the album, topping the [[UK Singles Chart]] and reaching a top three status on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100.<ref>{{cite web|last=Reigh|first=Len|title=Jennifer Lopez: J. LO|work=[[The Morning Call]]|location=Allentown, Pa.|format=Newspaper|date=January 27, 2001}}</ref> "[[Play (Jennifer Lopez song)|Play]]" was released as the second single, charting in the top twenty of the Hot 100 and reached three on the UK Singles Chart.<ref name="chart history1">{{cite web|title=Jennifer Lopez Chart History|url=http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/news/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=474548&zxtmsessid=4459230781#/artist/jennifer-lopez/chart-history/339297|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] (billboard.com)|accessdate=2012-01-29}}</ref> The album's third single "[[I'm Real/I'm Real (Murder Remix)|I'm Real]]" reached number one on the Hot 100, as well as spending over a year on the chart, with a total of 62 weeks.<ref name="chart history1"/> "I'm Real" was controversial for using a sample of the song "[[Yellow Magic Orchestra|Firecraker]]"—which singer [[Mariah Carey]] had wanted to sample first. It was later shockingly announced that Carey's ex husband, [[Tommy Mottola]] had instructed record executive Irv Gotti to give Lopez the sample before Carey, and Lopez was unaware of this.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mariah 'Ripped Off' Twice on Same Record|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,49437,00.html|publisher=[[Fox News Channel|Fox News]]|date=April 4, 2002|accessdate=2011-05-28}}</ref> "[[Ain't It Funny]]" was released as a single from ''J.Lo'', however it didn't receive a promotional release in the US and was ineligible to chart on the Hot 100. Lopez next film role was in a supernatural romance film, ''[[Angel Eyes (film)|Angel Eyes]]'' which disappointed at the box office and garnered mixed reviews.<ref>{{cite news|title=Lopez is simply out of sight in 'Angel Eyes'|accessdate=2012-01-30|newspaper=The Detroit News|date=May 18, 2001}}</ref> Lopez married former back-up dancer [[Cris Judd]] on September 29, 2001, at a home in the L.A. suburbs.<ref name=2ndweddingdetails>{{cite web|url=http://www.lovetripper.com/bridal/wedding-database/lopez-judd.html |title=Jennifer Lopez and Cris Judd Wedding |publisher=Lovetripper.com |date=September 29, 2001 |accessdate=2012-04-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Tabloids: Jennifer Lopez is expecting|work=[[Philadelphia Inquirer]]|date=June 13, 2001|quote=Tabloids in London and the Big Apple are reporting that Jennifer Lopez is preggers}}</ref> The following month, along with several other popular artists, Lopez was featured on an album featuring verses of the song "[[What's Going On (remix album)|What's Going On]]" under the name Artists Against AIDS Worldwide, to benefit AIDS foundations in Africa.<ref name=africa1 /><ref name=africa2 /> Produced before the [[September 11 attacks]], after the attacks the proceeds were given to [[American Red Cross]].<ref name=africa1>{{cite web|url=http://www.vh1.com/artists/news/1450245/20011022/ll_cool_j.jhtml |title=LL Cool J : LL Cool J, U2's Edge, More Join 'What's Going On' Project – Rhapsody Music Downloads |work=VH1 |accessdate=2012-03-23}}</ref><ref name=africa2>{{cite web|url=http://www.hopeforafricanchildren.org/New/Press/pr_103001.html |title=Artists Against AIDS Worldwide's New Superstar Version of Marvin Gaye's 'What's Going On' in Stores Tuesday, October 30 |publisher=Hopeforafricanchildren.org |date=October 30, 2001 |accessdate=2012-07-10}}</ref> The same month, Lopez was featured on the song "[[El Ultimo Adios (The Last Goodbye)]]" along with 60 other Latin artists, in memory of the September 11 attacks to help raise money for families and charities involved or affected.<ref name="artistlist">{{cite news |url=http://www.discogs.com/Various-El-Ultimo-Adios-The-Last-Goodbye/release/2075383|title=Complete list of 'El Ultimo Adios' artists |author=Stephanie J Stone |date=May 27, 2011 |work=Discogs.com |publisher=Discogs.com|accessdate=2010-02-17 | first=Stephanie | last=J Stone}}</ref>

=== 2002–04: ''J to tha L–O! The Remixes'', Bennifer and ''This Is Me... Then'' ===
{{Quote box|width=280px|align=left|quote="There was a time when I was very overworked and I was doing music and movies and so many things. I was suffering from a lack of sleep. And I did have a kind of nervous breakdown. I froze up on set. Well, not on a set, but in my trailer. I was like – I don't want to move, I don't want to talk, I don't want to do anything. It was on that movie, ''Enough''. Yeah, I did. I had a nervous breakdown."|source=—Jennifer Lopez
}}

Lopez's first remix album, ''[[J to tha L-O! The Remixes]]'' was released on February 5, 2002.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lopez|first=Jennifer|title=J to Tha L-O!: The Remixes|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/j-to-tha-l-o!-the-remixes-mw0000658032|publisher=[[Allmusic]]|accessdate=2012-10-20}}</ref> It debuted at the summit of the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], making it the first remix album in history to do so.<ref>{{cite web|last=Goodman|first=Abbey|title=Jennifer Lopez Kicks The Boys To The Curb On Next Week's Albums Chart Singer's remix album knocks Alan Jackson, Creed from top of Billboard 200|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1452273/jennifer-lopez-tops-albums-chart.jhtml|publisher=MTV (mtv.com)|accessdate=2012-01-29|date=February 13, 2002}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.famousqt.com/profile.asp?celeb=38 |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20070312090217/http://www.famousqt.com/profile.asp?celeb=38 |archivedate=2007-03-12 |title=Jennifer Lopez Biography Page |accessdate=2007-01-13 |work=FamousQT.com}}</ref> It also became the third highest-selling remix album in history, after [[Michael Jackson]]'s ''[[Blood on the Dance Floor: HIStory in the Mix]]'' and [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]'s ''[[You Can Dance]]''.<ref name="album sales">{{cite web|last=Trust|first=Gary|title=Ask Billboard: Analyzing 'American Idol'|url=http://www.billboard.com/column-chartbeat/ask-billboard-analyzing-american-idol-1004118716.story#/column-chartbeat/ask-billboard-analyzing-american-idol-1004118716.story|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] (billboard.com)|accessdate=2012-01-29|date=October 1, 2010}}</ref> The album spawned two commercially successful singles; the [[Murder, Inc.|murder remix]] version of "[[Ain't it Funny]]" featuring [[Ja Rule]] reached number one, followed by the Track Masters remix version of "[[I'm Gonna Be Alright]]" which peaked at ten.<ref name="chart history1"/><ref>{{cite web|title=More meat in the latest Red Hot Chili Peppers LP|url=http://www.philstar.com/Article.aspx?articleId=169636|work=The Philippine Star|accessdate=2012-01-29|date=July 26, 2002}}</ref> Another single written by Lopez and her then-husband Cris Judd, "[[Alive (Jennifer Lopez song)|Alive]]", served as the album's third single.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/news?utm_source=most_recent#/news/new-j-lo-song-on-remix-album-1302492.story |title=Latest Music News, Band, Artist, Musician & Music Video News |publisher=Billboard.com |date= |accessdate=2012-07-10}}</ref> In May, Lopez starred in the [[thriller (genre)|thriller]] film ''[[Enough]]'' as Slim, a woman abused by her husband who goes on the run. With a production budget of $38 million, the film grossed $52 million at the [[box office]] worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|title=Enough (2002)|url=http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=enough.htm|publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=2012-10-20}}</ref> While dubbed as a "kick-butt, female empowerment" movie,<ref>{{cite news|last=Schaefer|first=Stephen|title=MOVIES; Singer-actress Jennifer Lopez shows her strength in thriller `Enough'|accessdate=2012-01-30|newspaper=[[Boston Herald]]|date=May 19, 2002|location=Boston}}</ref> the film's reviews were negative,<ref>{{cite news|last=Nechak|first=Paula|title=J-Lo's latest tepid role will have audiences saying 'Enough'|url=http://www.seattlepi.com/ae/movies/article/J-Lo-s-latest-tepid-role-will-have-audiences-1087875.php|publisher=(seattlepi.com)|accessdate=2012-01-30|date=May 23, 2002}}</ref> although a fight scene between Slim and her husband at the film's conclusion was praised.<ref>{{cite news|title=Lopez mightily declares 'enough'|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=SB&p_theme=sb&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0F3BE83093DB8A38&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|accessdate=2012-01-30|date=May 24, 2002}}</ref> Despite being at the height of her fame, Lopez admitted to having a [[nervous breakdown]] while filming ''Enough''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Singh|first=Anita|title=Jennifer Lopez: I had a nervous breakdown|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/celebritynews/3152788/Jennifer-Lopez-I-had-a-nervous-breakdown.html|work=[[The Telegraph]]|accessdate=2012-10-20|date=October 7, 2008}}</ref> In June, Lopez filed for divorce from Judd and began publicly dating actor [[Ben Affleck]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Jennifer Lopez, husband Cris Judd split after 8 months of marriage|accessdate=2012-02-02|newspaper=San Jose Mercury News|date=June 8, 2002|location=California}}</ref> In November, Affleck proposed to Lopez and the couple became engaged.<ref>{{cite web|last=Silverman|first=Stephen|title=Ben's Proposal 'Beautiful,' Says Lopez|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,624998,00.html|work=[[People Magazine]]|accessdate=2012-10-20|date=November 11, 2002}}</ref><ref name="a">[http://et.tv.yahoo.com/movies/2004/01/22/benandjensplit Ben and Jen Split]</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Williams|first=Jeanne|title=J. Lo, Ben make first appearance as fiances|accessdate=2012-02-25|newspaper=[[USA Today]]|date=December 10, 2002|page=2}}</ref> The media began to refer to them as "Bennifer" and they became a prominent [[supercouple]] in the media and popular culture. Bennifer became a popular term, which was eventually entered into [[Urban Dictionary|urban dictionaries]] and [[neologism]] dictionaries as notable,<ref>{{cite web|title=Neologisms. These are neologisms collected by an undergraduate linguistics class at Rice University during the fall of 2003|publisher=ruf.rice.edu|accessdate=2007-06-22|url=http://www.ruf.rice.edu/~kemmer/Words04/neologisms/a.html#b}}</ref> and the name blend started the trend of other celebrity couples being referred to by the combination of each others' first names.<ref name="Celebrity Name Game">{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,1133516,00.html |title=Celebrity Name Game |publisher=People.com |date=November 23, 2005 |accessdate=2012-07-07}}</ref> 

[[File:Ben Affleck 2008.jpg|200px|thumb|right|Lopez and [[Ben Affleck]]'s (''pictured'') relationship attracted substantial media attention until their break up.]]

Lopez's third studio album ''[[This Is Me... Then]]'' was released on November 25.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.amazon.fr/This-Then-Jennifer-Lopez/dp/B000075AJB/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&qid=1341932338&sr=8-1 |title=This is Me ... Then: Jennifer Lopez: Amazon.fr: Musique |publisher=Amazon.fr |accessdate=2012-08-15}}</ref> The album's content reflected upon her relationship with Affleck; a song entitled "Dear Ben" detailed her relationship with the actor.<ref name=dedication>{{cite news|title=J-Lo disc declares her love|url=http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2002/11/27/1038274342213.html|work=The Age |location=Australia|accessdate=2012-01-29|date=November 27, 2002|location=Melbourne}}</ref> The album was proceeded by the release of lead single "[[Jenny from the Block]]". The next two singles released from ''This Is Me... Then'' were "[[I'm Glad]]" and "[[Baby I Love U!]]". Both failed to attain the success of her previous singles. The video for "I'm Glad" recreated scenes from the 1983 film ''[[Flashdance]]'', leading to a lawsuit over [[copyright infringement]], which was later dismissed.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://fwrv.com/articles/100757--life-story-releases-flashdance-chorus-line-.html |title=Life Story Releases: "Flashdance" & "Chorus Line" |author=Neil J. Rosini and Michael I Rudell |accessdate=2007-05-12 |work=[[New York Law Journal]] |date=October 27, 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hollywoodreporteresq.com/thresq/litigation/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1002651975 |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20070805150055/http://www.hollywoodreporteresq.com/thresq/litigation/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1002651975 |archivedate=2007-08-05 |title=9th Circuit Upholds Win for Lopez, Studios in 'Flashdance' Case |accessdate=2007-05-12 |author=Leslie Simmons |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=June 12, 2006}}</ref> ''This Is Me... Then'' has sold 2.6 million copies in the United States and has been certified double platinum by [[Recording Industry Association of America|RIAA]].<ref name="album sales" /> In December, Lopez starred opposite [[Ralph Fiennes]] in the romantic comedy film ''[[Maid in Manhattan]]''. She played Marisa Ventura, a struggling single mother who lives in the Bronx and makes her living cleaning rooms in a super-luxurious Manhattan hotel. Marisa gets mistaken for a socialite by a princely politician, who she falls in love with.<ref>Gary Susman (December 9, 2002). [http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,396721_12,00.html "Keeping It Reel"]. ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''. Retrieved 2009-06-24.</ref> With a production bugdet of $55 million, the film grossed $155 million at the box office worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|title=Maid in Manhattan|url=http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=maidinmanhattan.htm|publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=2012-10-20}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'' compared the film's storyline to her song "Jenny from the Block".<ref>A.O. Scott (December 13, 2002). [http://movies.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9A02E2D7133AF930A25751C1A9649C8B63 "Film Review; Puttin' Down Mop, Puttin' On the Ritz"]. ''The New York Times''. Retrieved 2009-06-24.</ref> 

In January 2003, Lopez and Judd's divorce was finalized.<ref name="wishes">{{cite news|title=P Diddy sends J-Lo wedding blessing|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/2458281.stm|publisher=BBC News (news.bbc.co.uk)|accessdate=2012-02-02|date=November 13, 2002}}</ref> In August, she starred opposite Affleck in the romantic comedy film ''[[Gigli]]'' as a lesbian. With a hefty production budget of $54 million, the film only grossed $7 million at the box office worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gigli (2003)|url=http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=gigli.htm|publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=2012-10-20}}</ref> It was considered a failure and one of the worst films ever made.<ref name=flopgigli>{{cite web|last=Taylor|first=Charles|title="Gligli" Jennifer Lopez|url=http://www.salon.com/2003/07/30/gigli/|publisher=(salon.com)|accessdate=2012-01-30|date=July 30, 2003}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Reviews are sour, but 'Gigli' fans like the eye candy|url=http://www.usatoday.com/life/movies/news/2003-08-03-gigli-reax_x.htm|publisher=[[USA Today]] (usatoday.com)|accessdate=2012-01-30|author=Julie Gordon and Steven Snyder|date=August 3, 2003}}</ref> In September, the couple canceled their wedding which had been scheduled for September 14 on the Californian Coast, citing the media's interference with the event as the reason.<ref>{{cite news|title=Media in frenzy over postponed 'Bennifer' wedding|url=http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2003/09/12/1063341766856.html|accessdate=2012-02-25|newspaper=[[The Age]]|date=September 13, 2003|location=Los Angeles}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Armstrong|first=Mark|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,624672,00.html|title=Lopez, Affleck Postpone Weekend Wedding|date=10 September 2003|''[[People (magazine)|People]]''|accessdate=2012-07-24}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Did Bennifer Follow Wedding Etiquette?|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,626828,00.html|accessdate=2012-02-25}}</ref> In January 2004, Lopez and Affleck broke up. Their split has been cited as being due to overexposure from the media, which caused public interest in their romance to result in less admiration and resulted in a negative impact on their careers.<ref name="www.Ew.com">{{cite news| first=Liane| last=Bonin | title=Pot Pans Kettle. Madonna calls J.Lo overexposed. The Material Girl says Bennifer could have avoided the media meltdown that postponed their wedding|work=Entertainment Weekly|date=October 31, 2003|accessdate=2009-07-06|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,536029,00.html}}</ref><ref name="www.people.com">{{cite news| first=Stephen M.| last=Silverman | title=Overexposed? Is There Too Much J.Lo?|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|date=December 9, 2002|accessdate=2009-07-06|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,625069,00.html}}</ref> In March, Lopez had a minor role in the film ''[[Jersey Girl (2004 film)|Jersey Girl]]'', alongside Affleck. Her character, Gertrude Steiney, dies during childbirth within the first 15 minutes of the film. From the intense media scrutiny following the couple's break-up, it was noted that "they may need to put Lopez in a coffin on the poster if they want anyone to come".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://today.msnbc.msn.com/id/4580539/ns/today-entertainment/t/marketing-jersey-girl-post-gigli-world/#.UHM3v03A-So |title=Marketing ‘Jersey Girl’ in a post-‘Gigli’ world - Entertainment - Movies - TODAY.com |publisher=Today.msnbc.msn.com |date=March 29, 2004 |accessdate=2012-10-20}}</ref> With a production budget of $35 million, the film was a commercial failure, earning a total of $36 million at the box office.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=jerseygirl.htm |title=Jersey Girl (2004) |publisher=Box Office Mojo |date= |accessdate=2012-10-20}}</ref> The film, however, received generally positive reviews from critics, despite being "full of cloyingly sentimental cliches".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/jersey_girl |title=Jersey Girl |publisher=Rotten Tomatoes |date= |accessdate=2012-10-20}}</ref> Lopez the began dating singer [[Marc Anthony]], who she had previous been involved with years ago. The couple wed on June 5, at her Beverly Hills Mansion, just one week after Anthony's divorce from [[Dayanara Torres]] was finalized.<ref>{{cite web|author=By&nbsp;Andrew Dansby |url=http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/j-lo-marc-anthony-marry-20040607 |title=J.Lo, Marc Anthony Marry &#124; Music News |work=Rolling Stone |date=June 7, 2004 |accessdate=2012-04-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Wedding highlights J.Lo's true talent: getting us talking|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=AASB&p_theme=aasb&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=1031F01295C1112D&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|accessdate=2012-02-25 | work=Austin American-Statesman|date=June 9, 2004}}</ref> Two men attempted to ransom a private wedding video which was stolen from the couple for one million dollars; however they were arraigned in Manhattan Criminal Court on charges of conspiracy, attempted grand larceny and possession of stolen property.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://msnbc.msn.com/id/10643569/site/todayshow/ns/today-entertainment/t/lopez-anthony-wedding-video-leads-arrests/#.T21q1RGPXi4 |title=Lopez-Anthony wedding video leads to arrests – Entertainment – Celebrities |publisher=MSNBC |accessdate=2012-04-01}}</ref> In October, Lopez co-starred alongside [[Richard Gere]] in the drama ''[[Shall We Dance? (2004 film)|Shall We Dance?]]'', a re-make of the [[Shall We Dance? (1996 film)|1996 Japanese film of the same title]]. With a production budget of $50 million, the film grossed a total of $170 million worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=shallwedance.htm |title=Shall We Dance (2004) |publisher=Box Office Mojo |date=February 24, 2005 |accessdate=2009-10-07}}</ref> It received generally positive reviews from critics, although it was noted that it "loses the nuances of the original", with the loss of cultural context and the addition of high-profile celebrities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/shall_we_dance |title=Shall We Dance |publisher=Rotten Tomatoes |date= |accessdate=2012-10-20}}</ref> Lopez starred in a [[Pepsi]] commercial featuring [[Beyoncé Knowles]] and [[David Beckham]] entitled "Samurai".<ref>{{cite news|title=For The Record: Quick News On Britney Spears, Paris Hilton, Sum 41, Lil' Kim, Gerald Levert, Morrissey & More |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1497582/20050228/spears_britney.jhtml |publisher=MTV News. MTV Networks |date=February 28, 2005 |accessdate=2008-04-03}}</ref>

=== 2005–07: ''Rebirth'', television production, ''Como Ama una Mujer'' and ''Brave'' ===
Lopez's fourth studio album ''[[Rebirth (Jennifer Lopez album)|Rebirth]]'' was released on March 1, 2005 in the United States.<ref name="lead single">{{cite web|title=Jennifer Lopez's new 'Rebirth' album to debut March 1|url=http://www.realitytvworld.com/news/jennifer-lopez-new-rebirth-album-debut-march-1-1000452.php|work=UPI News Service|publisher=realitytvworld.com|accessdate=2012-01-29|date=December 12, 2004}}</ref> The album was preceded by the release of two singles: "[[Get Right (Jennifer Lopez song)|Get Right]]" and "[[Hold You Down]]". "Get Right" was a commercial success, reaching the top spot in Hungary, Ireland, Italy and the United Kingdom and the top ten in various other countries, such Australia, Canada, Denmark, New Zealand and Spain. "Hold You Down" was a moderate success, peaking at number six in the United Kingdom and in the top twenty in most other countries. In May, Lopez starred alongside [[Jane Fonda]] in the romantic comedy ''[[Monster-in-Law]]''. She received $15&nbsp;million for her role as Charlie, an artist who is pitted against her fiance's mother when she does not accept her as being the right woman for her son.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.the-movie-times.com/thrsdir/actress/actressProfiles.mv?jlopez |title=Actress Jennifer Lopez [The Movie Times&#93; – Box Office, Movies, Gallery, Biography, and more |publisher=The-movie-times.com |accessdate=2009-10-07}}</ref><ref name=fonda>{{cite news|last=Lumenick|first=Lou|title=SO FONDA THE FIGHT|accessdate=2012-01-30|newspaper=[[New York Post]]|date=March 13, 2005|page=48}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Lowe|first=Kinsey R.|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2005/may/16/entertainment/et-boxoffice16|title='Monster-in-Law' gets a cheery reception; The comedy with Jane Fonda and Jennifer Lopez debuts at No.1 on another weekend off the pace set in 2004.|accessdate=2012-01-30|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=May 16, 2005|location=Los Angeles, California}}</ref> With a production budget of $43 million, the film grossed a total of $155 million worldwide.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=monsterinlaw.htm | title = Monster-in-Law (2005) | publisher = [[Box Office Mojo]]}}</ref> The film received generally negative reviews from film critics, who stated although Fonda "steals the show" in her "return to the screen", the "tired" script and "flimsy performances" make ''Monster-in-Law'' fall "flat".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/monsterinlaw |title=Monster-in-Law |publisher=Rotten Tomatoes |date=June 23, 2011 |accessdate=2012-08-08}}</ref> In August, Lopez starred alongside [[Robert Redford]] and [[Morgan Freeman]] in ''[[An Unfinished Life]]'', a drama film based on the novel of the same name. The film was a commercial failure, only grossing $18 million worldwide with its production budget of $30 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=unfinishedlife.htm |title=An Unfinished Life (2005) |publisher=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=2012-07-10}}</ref>

[[File:Time 100 Jennifer Lopez and Marc Antony.jpg|thumb|left|Lopez and Anthony at the Time 100 gala event on May 8, 2006]]

Lopez acted as the executive producer of ''[[South Beach (2006 TV series)|South Beach]]'', a primetime television drama that aired from January 6 to February 11, 2006 on [[UPN]].<ref name="South Beach Metacritic">{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/tv/south-beach |title=South Beach – Season 1 Reviews, Ratings, Credits, and More |publisher=Metacritic |date=January 11, 2006 |accessdate=2012-08-08}}</ref> The series, which stars [[Vanessa L. Williams]], follows three young adults "trying to get ahead in Miami".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1502639/record-j-lo-mandy-moore-amp-more.jhtml |title=For The Record: Quick News On Jennifer Lopez, Mandy Moore, Irv Gotti, Audioslave, Dido, Michelle Branch & More – Music, Celebrity, Artist News |publisher=MTV.com |date=May 19, 2005 |accessdate=2012-08-08}}</ref> The show experienced low ratings and received generally negative reviews from critics.<ref name="South Beach Metacritic"/> With UPN shutting down and moving its programming to [[The CW]] that fall, ''South Beach'' was one of many shows that weren't moved over to the new network.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvseriesfinale.com/tv-show/2006-cancelled-shows-upn-leaves-many-series-behind |title=2006 Cancelled Shows: UPN Leaves Many Series Behind &#124; canceled or renewed TV shows |publisher=TV Series Finale |date= |accessdate=2012-08-08}}</ref> In February, Lopez was featured on "[[Control Myself]]", the lead single from [[LL Cool J]]'s eleventh studio album ''[[Todd Smith (album)|Todd Smith]]'' (2006). The song was a commercial success, peaking at number four on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 and within the top ten internationally. Screenwriter Jack Bunick filed a lawsuit in April stating that the plot for ''South Beach'' was copied from ''South Beach Miami'', a script he wrote in 1999. Bunick claimed that he pitched the idea to UPN, but he was never contacted back.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/4945404.stm |title=Entertainment &#124; J-Lo sued over television series |publisher=BBC News |date=April 26, 2006 |accessdate=2012-08-08}}</ref> The lawsuit named Lopez, UPN, [[CBS Television]] and others as defendants. It was dropped in April 2008 by U.S. District Judge Richard Berman, who stated that there's inadequate evidence to take the case to trial.<ref>{{cite web|last=News |first=Daily |url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2008-04-30/gossip/29429340_1_judge-tosses-lawsuit-television-writer |title=Judge tosses out lawsuit against Jennifer Lopez – New York Daily News |publisher=Articles.nydailynews.com |date=April 30, 2008 |accessdate=2012-08-08}}</ref> On May 18, Lopez's film ''[[Bordertown (2006 film)|Bordertown]]'' made its premiere at the [[Cannes Film Festival]]. The film is based on the [[Female homicides in Ciudad Juárez]], a series of unsolved murders in [[Ciudad Juárez]], [[Chihuahua (state)|Chihuahua]], a [[maquiladora]] [[US-Mexico border|border]] city across the [[Río Bravo del Norte]] (Rio Grande) from [[El Paso, Texas]]. Lopez, who also acts as the film's producer, stars as Lauren Adrian, an American news reporter for the Chicago Sentinel who wants to be assigned to the Iraq front-lines to cover the war.<ref>{{cite news|last=Summers|first=Chris|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/5268558.stm|title=Hollywood tackles Mexican mystery|date=September 10, 2006|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=2012-07-24}}</ref> The film received a [[limited release]] in theaters throughout Europe in 2007 and a [[direct-to-video]] release in many other countries in 2008, including the United States. ''Bordertown'' was a commercial failure, grossing a total of $8 million worldwide, with its $21 million production budget.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=bordertown.htm |title=Bordertown |publisher=Box Office Mojo |date=July 8, 2012 |accessdate=2012-08-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abqtrib.com/news/2006/oct/19/nms-bordertown-hits-snag-loans |title=N.M.'s 'Bordertown' hits snag with loans : Local : Albuquerque Tribune |publisher=Abqtrib.com |date=October 19, 2006 |accessdate=2012-08-08}}</ref>

''[[DanceLife]]'', a reality series following the lives of seven dancers trying to break into the world of professional dance, aired on [[MTV]] from January 15, 2007 to March 5, 2007. Lopez produced, created and was featured in the show.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/shows/dancelife/series.jhtml |title=Dancelife &#124; Full Episodes, Photos, Episode Synopsis and Recaps |publisher=MTV |date= |accessdate=2012-08-08}}</ref> Lopez's fifth studio album ''[[Como Ama una Mujer]]'' was released on March 27, 2007 in the United States.<ref name="Como Allmusic">{{cite web|last=Thomas |first=Stephen |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/como-ama-una-mujer-mw0000484461 |title=Como Ama una Mujer – Jennifer Lopez : Songs, Reviews, Credits, Awards |publisher=AllMusic |date=March 27, 2007 |accessdate=2012-08-08}}</ref> According to Estéfano, the album's co-producer, the album will "prove critics wrong" from its "big songs that require a voice"; referring to the critics about Lopez having a "limited" vocal tone.<ref name="Contactmusic Rebirth">{{cite web|url=http://www.contactmusic.com/pages/jenniferlopezx18x03x05|title=Jennifer Lopez – Rebirth – Album Review|publisher=[[Contactmusic.com]]|accessdate=2012-04-01}}</ref><ref name="Contactmusic Spanish">{{cite web|url=http://www.contactmusic.com/news-article/j.lo-to-prove-critics-wrong-with-spanish-album_30_01_2006 |title=Jennifer Lopez – J.Lo To Prove Critics Wrong With Spanish Album – Contactmusic News |publisher=Contactmusic.com|date=January 30, 2006 |accessdate=2012-06-03}}</ref> The album was a natural and large success within the Latin community, reaching number one on [[Billboard Top Latin Albums|''Billboard'' Top Latin Albums]] chart, where it remained for seven weeks.<ref name="uscharts como">{{cite web|title=Como Ama una Mujer|url=http://www.billboard.com/#/album/jennifer-lopez/como-ama-una-mujer/899849|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|accessdate=2011-11-15}}</ref> Additionally, the album marks the highest first-week sales in the United States for a Spanish album and the highest digital sales.<ref name="Como Ama Una Mujer Breaks Records">{{cite web|title=Jennifer Lopez's First Spanish-Language Album is an Instant No. 1 on the Billboard Latin Chart: Como Ama Una Mujer Breaks Records with Highest Sales for an Artist's Debut Spanish-Language Album|url=http://www.prweb.com/releases/spanish/jennifer/prweb517033.htm|publisher=(prweb.com)|accessdate=2012-01-29|location=New York|date=April 6, 2007}}</ref> ''Como Ama una Mujer'' was preceded by the release of two singles: "[[Qué Hiciste]]" and "[[Me Haces Falta]]". "Qué Hiciste" peaked at number one on ''Billboard''{{'}}s [[Hot Latin Songs]] and [[Hot Dance Club Play]], while peaking at number eighty-six on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100.<ref name="chart history1"/> Internationally, the song was a commercial success, peaking atop the charts in Switzerland and Italy, and the top twenty in Austria, Belgium and Germany. "Me Haces Falta" failed to match the success of "Qué Hiciste", failing to chart on any national charts.

In August, Lopez released "[[Do It Well]]", the lead single from her sixth studio album ''[[Brave (Jennifer Lopez album)|Brave]]''. The song received positive reviews from music critics, who noted it to be a classic Lopez song, featuring dance elements and sassy lyrics.<ref name="Brave Rolling Stone">{{cite news|last=Ganz|first=Caryn|title=Jennifer Lopez: Brave: Music Reviews: Rolling Stone|url=http://www.rollingstone.com/artists/jenniferlopez/albums/album/16657741/review/16682672/brave|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20081227050103/http://www.rollingstone.com/artists/jenniferlopez/albums/album/16657741/review/16682672/brave|archivedate=2008-12-27|accessdate=2012-04-29|newspaper=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=October 18, 2007}}</ref> It was a moderate commercial success, reaching the top twenty in almost every country it was released. On September 28, Lopez and Anthony launched their [[Jennifer Lopez and Marc Anthony en Concierto|co-headlining]] North American concert tour. The tour grossed an estimated $10 million, with one dollar from each ticket sold being donated to Run for Something Better—a charitable organization supporting physical fitness programs for children.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Cobo, Leila|date=7 June 2008|title=Together Again|journal=Billboard|volume=120|issue=23|location=New York City, New York|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc|issn=0006-2510|accessdate=2012-05-28|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=_hIEAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA1&pg=PA10#v=onepage&q&f=false|page=10}}</ref><ref name="ld1">{{cite web|url=http://www.soundspike.com/story2/12624/jennifer-lopez-to-drop-brave-new-album/|title=Jennifer Lopez to drop 'Brave' new album|last=Kilgore|first=Kym|date=August 13, 2007|accessdate=2010-09-04|work=LiveDaily|archiveurl=http://www.freezepage.com/1338238555ICJBKARMZN |archivedate=2012-05-28}}</ref> ''Brave'' was released on October 9, 2007 in the United States, peaking at number twelve on the ''Billboard'' 200 and becoming her lowest-charting album worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|last=Thomas |first=Stephen |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/brave-mw0000495603 |title=Brave – Jennifer Lopez : Songs, Reviews, Credits, Awards |publisher=AllMusic |date=October 9, 2007 |accessdate=2012-08-08}}</ref><ref name=lovereview>{{cite web|last=Copsey|first=Robert|title=Jennifer Lopez: 'Love?'|url=http://www.digitalspy.com.au/music/albumreviews/a317729/jennifer-lopez-love.html|work=[[Digital Spy]]|publisher=(digitalspy.com)|accessdate=2012-01-29|date=May 4, 2011}}</ref> A five-part [[miniseries]], ''[[Jennifer Lopez Presents: Como Ama una Mujer]]'', based on the lyrics of ''Como Ama una Mujer'' aired on [[Univision]] from October 30 to November 27, 2007. The miniseries follows Sofia (portrayed by [[Leonor Varela]]), a famous singer and actress whose rise to superstardom happened overnight, who finds her private life to be constantly under attack by the paparazzi.<ref name="Univision Como">{{cite web|url=http://corporate.univision.com/2007/press/univision-and-nuyorican-productions-announce-all-star-cast-for-jennifer-lopez-produced-dramatic-mini-series-%E2%80%9Ccomo-ama-una-mujer%E2%80%9D/|title=Univision And Nuyorican Productions Announce All-Star Cast For Jennifer Lopez Produced Dramatic Mini-Series "Como Ama Una Mujer"|publisher=Univision|accessdate=2011-10-30}}</ref> On November 7, during the final night of their tour, Lopez and Anthony officially confirmed that they were expecting their first child together.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7084486.stm|title=Singer Lopez confirms pregnancy|work=BBC |date=November 8, 2007|accessdate=2007-11-09}}</ref> The announcement ended months of speculation over the pregnancy, which was deemed by the media to be the worst kept secret of the year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollyscoop.com/jennifer-lopez/roberto-cavalli-confirms-jlos-pregnancy.html |title=Roberto Cavalli Confirms J.Lo's Pregnancy – Jennifer Lopez |publisher=Hollyscoop.com |date= |accessdate=2012-03-21}}</ref> "[[Hold It Don't Drop It]]" was released as the second and final single from ''Brave''; peaking atop the ''Billboard'' Hot Dance Club Play chart, giving Lopez her third consecutive number one single on that chart.<ref name="chart history1"/>

=== 2008–11: Motherhood, ''Love?'' and ''American Idol'' ===
[[File:Martakis jennifer lopez.jpg|thumb|right|Lopez with Anthony and Greek singer [[Kostas Martakis]], who opened her September 2008 concert in Athens]]

On February 6, 2008, it was revealed that Lopez and Anthony were expecting twins. Her father announced the news, stating: "Yes, twins. The thing is in my family, my sister also had twins, so it's a hereditary thing".<ref>http://www.nme.com/news/jennifer-lopez/34139</ref> Later that same month, Lopez released her seventh fragrance Deseo.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://voices.yahoo.com/deseo-jennifer-lopez-perfume-review-1045285.html?cat=46 |title=Deseo by Jennifer Lopez Perfume Review – Yahoo! Voices |publisher=voices.yahoo.com |date= |accessdate=2012-08-08}}</ref> On February 22, Lopez gave birth to a son, Maximilian David, and a daughter, Emme Maribel, in [[Long Island]], New York.<ref name="Welcomes Twins">{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20171851,00.html|date=February 22, 2008|title=Jennifer Lopez & Marc Anthony Welcome Twins!|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|accessdate=2008-02-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20181407,00.html|title=Jennifer Lopez & Marc Anthony Reveal Baby Names|work=[[People (magazine)|People]] |accessdate=2008-02-29}}</ref> The twins were introduced in the March 11, 2008 issue of ''People'', for which the magazine paid a reported $6&nbsp;million—the photographs of the twins became [[List of most expensive celebrity photographs|the most expensive celebrity picture ever taken]] at the time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.forbes.com/2009/07/01/michael-jackson-magazine-business-media-jackson.html |title=Jackson Pic Won't Make List Of Priciest Celeb Photos |publisher=Forbes.com |date= |accessdate=2012-03-21}}</ref> While pregnant with her children, Lopez began working on new music for a future project.<ref name="MTV 2009-06-15">{{cite web |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1613887/jennifer-lopez-talks-about-influence-her-twins-on-new-music.jhtml |title=Jennifer Lopez Talks About Influence Of Her Twins on New Music |work=MTV News |publisher=[[MTV Networks]] ([[Viacom]]) |last=Carol |first=Larry |date=June 15, 2009 |accessdate=2011-02-05}}</ref> Lopez's next musical project was kept under wraps until February 2009 when a new song from the recording sessions leaked online.<ref name="Hooked on you">{{cite web |url=http://www.hollyscoop.com/music/jennifer-lopez/first-listen-jennifer-lopez-hooked-on-you_1479.aspx |title=First Listen: Jennifer Lopez Hooked on You |publisher=Hollyscoop (DNA Group Inc.) |last=Daly |first=Bridget |date=February 23, 2009 |accessdate=2011-02-05}}</ref> Following this, several other songs were leaked online, that were, at the time, meant to appear on a greatest hits album; that would later turn into a studio album.<ref name="Rap-Up What Is Love?">{{cite web|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2009/05/12/new-music-jennifer-lopez-what-is-love |title=New Music: Jennifer Lopez – "What Is Love" |publisher=''[[Rap-Up]]''. Devin Lazerine |date=May 12, 2009 |accessdate=2012-06-04}}</ref> In June, Lopez told [[MTV]]'s Larry Carol that the songs hinted at the musical direction of her then-upcoming seventh studio album. She also stated that she was keen to finish the album and several singles, with a potential release date for the end of 2009.<ref name="MTV 2009-06-15"/> In late summer, Lopez released Sunkissed Glow, the fourth flanker fragrance of Glow by J.Lo.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.perfume.com/jennifer-lopez/sunkissed-glow/women-perfume |title=Jennifer Lopez Perfume, Jennifer Lopez Sunkissed Glow, Perfume Deals : Shop |publisher=Perfume.com |date=August 7, 2009 |accessdate=2012-08-08}}</ref> On October 7, Lopez released her twelfth fragrance My Glow. Described as a "feminine, skin floral fragrance", My Glow contains notes that create a "subtle, yet fresh scent". The shape of the bottle is inspired by soaps from Lopez's nursery and the [[cherub]] cap is dual-sided to represent each of her twins: one side a baby boy and the other a girl.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.realstylenetwork.com/blogs/beauty/2009/10/jennifer-lopez-launches-my-glow |title=JENNIFER LOPEZ LAUNCHES "MY GLOW" " Real Style Network – Beauty |publisher=Real Style Network |date=October 6, 2009 |accessdate=2012-08-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Oct 7, 2009 @ 9:00 am |url=http://news.instyle.com/2009/10/07/exclusive-photo-jennifer-lopez-in-the-my-glow-campaign |title=EXCLUSIVE PHOTO: Jennifer Lopez in the My Glow Campaign : InStyle.com What's Right Now |publisher=News.instyle.com |date=October 7, 2009 |accessdate=2012-08-08}}</ref> Later that same day, a song entitled "[[Fresh Out the Oven]]" featuring Miami rapper [[Pitbull (rapper)|Pitbull]] surfaced online.<ref>{{Cite journal|first=David |last=Caplan |date=October 7, 2009|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20310928,00.html|work=[[People (magazine)|People]] |accessdate=2009-10-10 | title=First listen: Jennifer Lopez's Dance Track 'Fresh Out of the Oven'|ref=harv}}</ref> Following the leak, the song was issued as a [[buzz single]] and managed to peak atop the US ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Hot Dance Club Songs]] chart.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/#/charts/dance-club-play-songs?chartDate=2010-01-30 |title=Dance/Club Play Songs – Week of January 30, 2010 |work=Billboard |publisher=Nielsen Business Media |accessdate=2011-01-05}}</ref> Lopez released "[[Louboutins (song)|Louboutins]]", a song written and produced by [[The-Dream]] and [[Tricky Stewart]], as the project's lead single in November 2009.<ref name="Rap-Up Lopez Gets Louboutins">{{cite web|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2009/10/28/jennifer-lopez-walks-in-brandys-louboutins/#more-29927 |title=Jennifer Lopez Walks in Brandy's 'Louboutins' |publisher=''[[Rap-Up]]''. Devin Lazerine |date=October 28, 2009 |accessdate=2009-10-28}}</ref> However, upon release, the song failed to garner enough airplay to chart, despite topping the US ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Hot Dance Club Songs]] chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/column/chartbeat/oscar-winners-on-the-hot-100-1004073779.story?tag=hppromo4#/column/chart-highlights-adult-contemporary-country-1004073580.story?tag=nextartb|title= Chart Highlights: Adult Contemporary, Country Songs & More |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] |accessdate=2010-03-10}}</ref>

Lopez parted ways with Epic Records in February 2010, citing that she had fulfilled her contractual obligations and now wished to release her seventh studio album, ''[[Love?]]'', under a new label.<ref name="Billboard Lopez Leaves Sony">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/news/updated-jennifer-lopez-confirms-split-with-1004070556.story?tag=hpfeed#/news/updated-jennifer-lopez-confirms-split-with-1004070556.story?tag=hpfeed |title=UPDATED: Jennifer Lopez Confirms Split With Epic Records |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] | author= Concepcion, Mariel; Ben-Yehuda, Ayala; Caulfield, Kieth |date=February 23, 2010 |accessdate=2010-03-16}}</ref> Her departure from the label temporarily halted production on the album, however upon signing a new contract with [[Island Records]], recording resumed on the album.<ref>{{cite web|author=Sarah |url=http://www.usmagazine.com/entertainment/news/record-producer-spills-justin-bieber-katy-perry-and-j-los-studio-secrets-2010167 |title=Record Producer Spills Justin Bieber, Katy Perry and J.Lo's Studio Secrets |work=[[Us Weekly]] |publisher=[[Wenner Media]] |date=June 16, 2010 |accessdate=2010-10-02}}</ref> The ''[[Daily News (New York)|New York Daily News]]'' revealed that Lopez would be taking some of the records recorded under Sony Music Entertainment to her new label so that they could be included on the album.<ref>{{cite news|author=Gatecrasher |url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2010-02-24/gossip/27057095_1_el-cantante-sony-music-second-source |title=After 'Louboutins', 'Fresh Out of the Oven' flop, Epic Records gives Jennifer Lopez the boot |work=[[Daily News (New York)|New York Daily News]] |publisher=[[New York Times Company]] |date=February 24, 2010 |accessdate=2012-05-04}}</ref> In March 2010, Lopez guest starred on an episode of ''[[How I Met Your Mother]]'' as Anita Appleby, a no-nonsense author of self-help books that teach women how to mold men into "relationship machines" through the power of denial.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.tvguide.com/News/Jennifer-Lopez-Guest-1014258.aspx|title= Jennifer Lopez to Meet ''Mother''s Barney|publisher=TVGuide.com}}</ref> Later that same month, Lopez launched Blue Glow, the fifth flanker to Glow by J.Lo. It was described as a "fresh, sexy and enticing" fragrance. The perfume is made of fruits, florals and woods with many different ingredients. The fragrance was initially available exclusively at [[HSN]] and was later made available at [[Sears]], [[Macy's]] and [[Sephora]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.realstylenetwork.com/blogs/beauty/2010/03/jennifer-lopez-launches-blue-glow-fragrance |title=Jennifer Lopez Launches Blue Glow Fragrance " Real Style Network – Beauty |publisher=Real Style Network |date=March 29, 2010 |accessdate=2012-08-08}}</ref> In April, Lopez starred in the [[romantic comedy film|romantic comedy]] ''[[The Back-up Plan]]'', her first theatrical role in three years.<ref name="Rovi Back Up Plan">{{cite web|first=Jason |last=Buchanan |url=http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/the-back-up-plan-v490905 |title=The Back-up Plan – Cast, Reviews, Summary, and Awards |work=AllRovi |publisher=Rovi Corporation |accessdate=2011-10-30}}</ref> With a $35 million production budget, the film grossed $77 million worldwide.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=backupplan.htm |title=The Back-up Plan (2010) |work=Box Office Mojo| publisher=Amazon.com |accessdate=2011-11-27}}</ref> While Lopez's acting in the film was praised, the film was criticized for for its "unrelatable characters" and "predictable plot".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/back_up_plan |title=The Back-up Plan |publisher=Rotten Tomatoes |date= |accessdate=2012-08-08}}</ref> In June, following the departure of [[Ellen DeGeneres]] from ''[[American Idol]]'', it was reported that Lopez was in talks to join season ten's judging panel.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usmagazine.com/celebritynews/news/source-jennifer-lopez-to-be-an-american-idol-judge-2010307 |title=Source: Jennifer Lopez to Be an American Idol Judge – Celebrity News |publisher=UsMagazine.com |accessdate=2011-08-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/tv/2010/07/29/2010-07-29_ellen_degeneres_leaving_american_idol.html | location=New York | work=Daily News | title=Ellen DeGeneres leaves 'American Idol'; Jennifer Lopez reportedly close to replacing her | first=Bill | last=Hutchinson | date=July 30, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/showtracker/2010/07/american-idols-backup-plan-with-jennifer-lopez-not-ready-for-delivery.html | work=The Los Angeles Times | title=Show Tracker | date=July 30, 2010}}</ref> During this same time, Lopez and Anthony were being considered for a role on ''[[The X Factor (U.S.)|The X Factor]]'' for their appeal to Latin and International markets.<ref>{{cite web|author=Thursday, May 13, 2010, 13:29 BST |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/ustv/s103/the-x-factor/news/a219700/lopez-anthony-linked-to-us-x-factor.html |title=US TV – News – Lopez, Anthony linked to US 'X Factor' |publisher=Digital Spy |date=May 13, 2010 |accessdate=2010-09-18}}</ref> It was officially announced in September that Lopez would be joining the [[American Idol (season 10)|tenth season]] of ''American Idol''. [[MTV]] stated that the deal was "mutually beneficial to all those involved", while [[CNN]] reported that Lopez was viewing it as a decision to revive her career, while ''American Idol'' producers believed that Lopez and [[Steven Tyler]]'s appointments would strengthen viewing figures.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://edition.cnn.com/2010/SHOWBIZ/TV/09/22/jennifer.lopez.american.idol/ |publisher=CNN | title=Jennifer Lopez: A reality TV revival? | date=September 23, 2010}}</ref> In October, Lopez released her fourteenth fragrance, Love and Glamour. The perfume was inspired by Lopez's "return to the spotlight".<ref>{{cite web|author=Jun 7, 2010 @ 3:07 pm |url=http://news.instyle.com/2010/06/07/jennifer-lopez-launches-love-and-glamour |title=Jennifer Lopez Launches Love and Glamour : InStyle.com What's Right Now |publisher=News.instyle.com |date=June 7, 2010 |accessdate=2012-08-08}}</ref> [[L'Oreal Paris]] named Lopez their new Global Ambassador and the face of their brands, including EverPure hair care, Preference hair color and Youth Code skin care, in December 2010. Her ads for EverSleek hair care made their debut in early 2011, to coincide with the release of ''Love?'' and her debut as a judge on ''America Idol''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.realstylenetwork.com/blogs/beauty/2010/12/jennifer-lopez-named-loreal-paris-global-ambassador |title=Jennifer Lopez Named L'Oreal Paris Global Ambassador " Real Style Network – Beauty |publisher=Real Style Network |date=December 3, 2010 |accessdate=2012-08-08}}</ref> To further promote her comeback, in February 2011, [[Venus]] chose Lopez as their new Global Ambassador. She appeared in their Gillette Venus ads, which featured Lopez covering the Venus theme song "Yeah Baby, She's Got It" for the commercials.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.realstylenetwork.com/blogs/beauty/2011/02/jennifer-lopez-is-the-new-venus-global-ambassador |title=Jennifer Lopez Is The New Venus Global Ambassador " Real Style Network – Beauty |publisher=Real Style Network |date=February 3, 2011 |accessdate=2012-08-08}}</ref>

